<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: HOW MANY POINTS FOR T-R-U-M-P? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 U.S. toy maker Mattel Inc. on Friday announced a $78.32-million offer for 
British games maker J.W. Spear & Sons, a last-minute bid to spoil the party for 
main competitor Hasbro Inc. 
</P>
<P>
 Spear is best known for holding the rights outside the United States to the 
popular word game Scrabble. 
</P>
<P>
 The move again pits Mattel against archrival Hasbro. Mattel last year dropped 
a multimillion-dollar lawsuit after Hasbro agreed to make its best-selling 
doll, Sindy, look less like Mattel's Barbie. Hasbro is the largest American toy 
company and owns the U.S. rights to Scrabble. 
</P>
<P>
 Mattel's cash offer values each Spear share at $15, trumping the $13.50 on the 
table from Hasbro. Spear's board immediately backed the higher offer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
