<P>
 Wal-Mart Predicts $84 Billion in Sales: Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the retailing 
company started by Sam Walton just over two decades ago in rural Arkansas, is 
poised to top $100 billion in sales next year and become the world's largest 
company not too long after. Already the world's biggest retailer, Wal-Mart told 
shareholders at its annual meeting in Fayetteville, Ark., that its sales this 
year will soar to $84 billion."At the current rate of growth of 25%, Wal-Mart 
sales will hit $100 billion by 1995," said John Eade, retail analyst at Argus 
Research. That will put it in an elite club of giant oil and auto companies 
that have reached that lofty sales level. And if it maintains its longstanding 
growth rate of roughly 20% a year, it will challenge General Motors Corp. as 
the world leader in sales just two years after. GM's sales are about $135 
million, and it has a much slower growth rate. 
