ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hick; Davan Maharaj, SILVERSTE; Rick VanderKnyff 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 PRO-BARBRA: Barbra Streisand found out at her opening concert at The Pond of 
Anaheim Thursday night (F1) that Orange County folks love her. But not 
necessarily all her causes. . . . The audience applauded her mention of South 
Africa's recent elections and wildly cheered scenes of marchers with pro-choice 
on abortion placards shown during a video montage. But Bill Clinton's picture 
did little for the crowd, even though Streisand hailed the President for having 
"an exciting and productive year.". . . . Streisand returns to The Pond 
tonight. 
</P>
<P>
 BARRED AGAIN: For 10 years, Thomas F. Maniscalco dutifully paid his State Bar 
of California dues with the hopes of resuming his law career if ever released 
from jail. But now that Maniscalco, 49, has been convicted of second-degree 
murder March 15 for a Westminster triple slaying, he can stop paying those 
dues. . . . The State Bar Court this week suspended him. Maniscalco, scheduled 
for a June 24 sentencing, can be reinstated only if he is successful on his 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
 PRESSING ON: Liberal radio-TV commentator Bill Press will do a little 
political one-on-one with shoppers when he takes his KFI 640 AM radio talk show 
to Fashion Island at noon today. KFI spokesman William Lewis says Press wanted 
to do a show in Orange County to face off with opinionated shoppers in 
"deepest, darkest Republicanville." . . . Typical of Press, who is also state 
Democratic Party chairman, he recently confronted conservative Dan Quayle at a 
book signing. 
</P>
<P>
 POLITICAL SPLIT: It's official: Longtime local political consultant Harvey 
Englander will split from partners Dan Wooldridge and Jerry Pierson over "a 
difference in philosophy." Their firm has a hand in the county campaigns of 
supervisor candidate Haydee V. Tillotson and 70th Assembly District contender 
Marilyn C. Brewer. . . . Wooldridge, an ex-aide to two former county 
supervisors, will stay with Pierson. Englander says he will merge with a 
Washington-based political firm. 
</P>
