<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: SIMI VALLEY; NEW RECREATION CENTER SET TO OPEN JUNE 
20 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY F. POLS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With nothing in her new office but the smell of fresh paint and a plastic 
child's chair, Tracy Engel is already hard at work in her new job as recreation 
supervisor for the just-completed Rancho Santa Susana Community Center in Simi 
Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 "I won't be spending much time at my desk anyway," Engel said, walking across 
the glossy floor of the 11,686-square-foot gymnasium. "We'll have something 
going on in every room. That will require us to be up and about all the time." 
</P>
<P>
 Engel officially starts her new job Monday. Her first action will be to get 
ready for a public dedication of the facility on June 18, with an open house 
that will include games, prizes and clowns. 
</P>
<P>
 On June 20, the center officially opens with summer classes in dance, crafts 
and sports. 
</P>
<P>
 Before joining Rancho Simi Recreation and Park District, Engel worked for the 
Conejo Valley Recreation and Park District for 10 years, most recently as 
program coordinator of the teen center. 
</P>
<P>
 Park district Administrator Jeff Anderson said Engel was selected from a pool 
of 55 candidates for the position. 
</P>
<P>
 He said his nervousness about opening the vast new facility had almost 
vanished after Engel agreed to take the job. 
</P>
<P>
 "I've been sleeping a lot better lately," Anderson said. "She's been in 
centers for 10 years, she's got more experience than we do. We've never run a 
center like this one." 
</P>
<P>
 Engel, a resident of Moorpark, studied recreation administration at Chico 
State. Her pride in the new center was obvious on a recent tour of the gray 
stone facility. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to the gymnasium, which can accommodate three basketball games 
simultaneously, the center has a catering kitchen, circular dance studio, 
locker rooms and two large multipurpose rooms. 
</P>
<P>
 Engel said the district hopes to rent out the multipurpose rooms for wedding 
receptions and parties. 
</P>
<P>
 She said several brides had already reserved the space for summer weddings. 
</P>
<P>
 Pointing out warming trays, rows of industrial-sized refrigerators and an ice 
machine in the center's catering kitchen, she said the center could handle any 
size group, from 10 to 1,000. 
</P>
<P>
 "There is no limit to what we can do," she said. "We're set up to handle just 
about everything." 
</P>
<P>
 But recreation is still the focus of the center. Looking out at the smooth 
expanse of floor in the gymnasium, Engel turned to Anderson. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've got to get a ball down here," she told him. MARY F. POLS 
</P>
</TEXT>
